er West Papua, including Yonggom experiences as political refugees in Papua New Guinea. The author challenges a prevailing homogenization in current representations of indigenous peoples, showing how Yonggom modes of analysis specifically have shaped these political movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362574740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625747/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles